recordings.rmk:
I apologize for adding two sets of calls from a Willow Warbler. The reason is to facilitate a comparison between individuals. In fact, the first clip is a spring adult from April; the second clip (0:19) is an autumn bird, possibly a juvenile (although I don't know), recorded on 1st August. If you wish to click and hear the equivalent calls from Chiffchaffs, they are here: XC562501

Just in case listeners think that the first calls are actually from a Chiffchaff (because you can hear snatches of Chiffchaff song at 0:02 and 0:08) I can confirm that BOTH species were present in the area. These calls are from a Willow Warbler that I could see - and it was singing during about 95% of the time. It called very little - and probably would not have called at all except for the fact that it could see me.

recordings.file-name: XC419334-mixed singing from a male Willow Warbler in response to playback of Common Chiffchaff song Monahan Road 7th June 2018_HH_1.mp3
recordings.rmk:
As a brief experiment, I played some Common Chiffchaff song within earshot of a male Willow Warbler on territory at a site which, as far as I am aware, doesn't hold Common Chiffchaff (certainly, none were heard during my visit), as the Willow Warbler had given one or two slightly mixed phrases of song amongst strophe after strophe of perfect Willow Warbler song. Shortly after my doing so, the bird came closer: initially, I hadn't seen that it had flown across to some scrub, and I assumed I had inadvertently upset an unseen silent Common Chiffchaff, even if the song wasn't quite perfect for that species. Certainly, at that stage, there were no typical Willow Warbler song elements.
However, as the song went on, possibly owing to the bird believing that it had driven of the mysterious congener, it gave a few strophes of mixed song, these began as for Common Chiffchaff with a terminal descending series of notes as in Willow Warbler. After a while, it then settled into giving typical Willow Warbler song again.
While it is impossible to be sure of the bird's genetic provenance without a DNA sample, it did look pretty much like a typical Willow Warbler, and it also sounded like one most of the time. Interestingly, I had a mixed singing Willow Warbler at the same site in spring 2017, and one would assume that this is the same bird having returned. As per a short paper in the latest issue of British Birds, it is quite possible, given the suboptimal nature of the habitat, neither typical of Willow Warbler or Common Chiffchaff, that there is somehow heightened territorial competition between both species in such areas.
High pass filter applied below 2kHz, and a short segment of the recording with talking on has been edited out, otherwise as recorded.

recordings.rmk: This recording provides a link between a Willow Warbler apprentice whose calls are at a primitive stage of development (XC196850) and an individual that, although probably juvenile, has already acquired the dulcet ring of the species (XC196849). The various utterances are somewhat variable and provide, I think, a fascinating example of a juvenile practicing until it gets the hang of the call. The initial attempts are certainly along the right lines and it produces an almost perfect note at 0:19 only to 'lose the plot' with some of the final stabs, such as 0:23. However, over subsequent days, practice no doubt made perfect.

recordings.loc: Oxford Island, Lough Neagh, Co. Armagh, Northern Ireland
recordings.file-name: XC196850-Willow Warbler scraping call of juv Ox Is 5 Aug 2013 0854hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: Many young Willow Warblers in extensive shoreline willow scrub reflected, over the summer, the phase of development of their call note from 'rough rookie' to the silky quality of adulthood. This recording features the rough and scraping attempts of, presumably, the very youngest. The quality is even reminiscent of the flight call of a Common Snipe. Other individuals, more advanced in their acquisition of their species-specific calls, are XC196851 (whose voice was still a 'work in progress') and XC196849.

recordings.rmk:
An aberrant Phylloscopus, very likely Willow Warbler. 

This bird sang in a quite open area with some taller birches. The song resembled either Eastern or Western Bonelli's Warbler P.bonelli/orientalis. It seemed that the song was audible only part of the time which the bird could be seen uttering its phrase. It did not react to the song of Bonelli's Warbler or its own song, but it did to the song of Willow Warbler. Some hours later the phrase changed temporarily to resemble Willow Warbler slightly more.

Photos here:
<http://www.elisanet.fi/antero.lindholm/Linnut/Phylloscopus/lohja.html>

Calls of a pair, moving around in trees. Male call is slighly lower and ending less ascending, but in each is also variation. c. 265 calls and 19 songs in the recording. Recording distance 10-20 m. [52.07279118814076, 4.452387392466335]

An aberrant song. The bird looks like a Willow Warbler and reacted to playback of (normal song of) that species.  The bird has held its territory for several weeks. The recording is quite strongly filtered and a couple of passing cars have been cut away.

recordings.rmk: Mixed singer. Same bird as __XC133049__. This bird looked absolutely like a normal Willow Warbler, showing no aberrant features.
